Incoming F.C.C. chair Brendan Carr has said a lot of crazy things,
but he=E2=80=99s right to question the outdated rules on TV station ownersh=
ip limits. Why should streaming platforms like YouTube and Netflix get to c=
hase 100 percent of viewers and advertising while, say, Tegna or Scripps, d=
eliver the same product=E2=80=94ad-supported video=E2=80=94yet are limited =
to TV stations that reach only 39 percent of U.S. households? Those limits =
won=E2=80=99t completely disappear under Carr, but expect them to be relaxe=
d, which should lead to a frenzy of mergers among station groups. That=E2=
=80=99s
especially true if R.F.K. Jr. succeeds in his improbable push to ban lucrat=
ive pharma ads, which would hit station groups hard. Even the network owner=
s like Paramount, Disney, and NBCUniversal could potentially buy up more of=
 their affiliates.

13. Avatar 3 Flies Higher Than Avatar 2
---------------------------------------

By Scott Mendelson, What I=E2=80=99m
Hearing=E2=80=99s resident box office expert

=C2=A0

Here=E2=80=99s a hot take: James Cameron=E2=80=99s Avatar: Fire and Ash wil=
l not just become the top global grosser of 2025, but also the director=E2=
=80=99s fourth $2 billion-plus earner. Right now, conventional wisdom has i=
t that Avatar 3 will rake in ridiculous amounts of cash, but less than the =
first two=E2=80=94Avatar made $2.7 billion in 2010, not
adjusted for inflation and not counting reissues, and The Way of Water pull=
ed in $2.32 billion in 2022. There are reasons to believe the series=E2=80=
=99 trajectory might more closely mirror the first two Star Wars trilogies,=
 wherein part three earned less than the first chapter, yet more than the s=
econd. That outcome, at least partially, will depend on moviegoers in China=
=2E=C2=A0

=C2=A0

We don=E2=80=99t
know whether Avatar 2=E2=80=99s $246 million gross in China was due to decl=
ining interest in Hollywood tentpoles or its Covid-era release. While highe=
r than any Hollywood tentpole thus far this decade, it was barely more than=
 the $203 million Avatar earned there in 2010, and that was with far fewer =
available screens. Meanwhile, assuming Fire and Ash is comparable in qualit=
y and appeal, global interest should remain on par with its predecessor. Th=
row in a dash of domestic
inflation, fewer mid-to-late-December films to compete with, and a China re=
lease potentially closer to what was hoped for last time around, and Fire a=
nd Ash could become Cameron=E2=80=99s third $2.4 billion-plus grosser.

=C2=A0

