argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">On Saturday night, five of the top 10 movies on=
 Netflix were from
Warner Bros. That=E2=80=99s actually not that unusual these days. Since Dav=
id Zaslav started upending every couch cushion in search of licensing nicke=
ls, title after title has been whored out to the highest bidder=E2=80=94oft=
en Netflix=E2=80=94and often nonexclusively, so the movies remain on Max wh=
ile everyone watches them on Netflix, thus obviating the need to pay for Ma=
x.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
:0;margin-bottom:0px;">But these five movies in the Netflix top 10 were all
from <em>this</em> spring and summer: <em>Dune: Part Two</em>, <em>Godzilla=
 x Kong: The New Empire</em>, <em>Furiosa: A Mad Max Saga</em>, <em>Watcher=
s</em>, and my favorite, <em>Horizon: An American Saga: Part One</em>, whic=
h was at No. 2! (Release <em>Part Two</em>, you cowards!) One after another=
, from <em>Barbie</em> and <em>Wonka</em> on the film side, to such classic=
 HBO series as <em>Sex and the City</em>, <em>Band of Brothers</em>, and <e=
m>Six Feet Under</em>, it=E2=80=99s been a parade of
former Max exclusives on Netflix.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Except <em>The Sopran=
os</em>. <strong>David Chase</strong>=E2=80=99s signature HBO show has been=
 deemed off-limits. But I=E2=80=99m betting that changes this year. The eco=
nomics of Warner Discovery=E2=80=99s linear business aren=E2=80=99t getting=
 better, the film studio has a super-risky slate, and nothing suggests Zaz =
is any less interested in licensing cash. Even <em>The West Wing</em>, a pe=
rennial
performer on Max, was just yanked in the hope of generating a big licensing=
 deal for WBTV. It=E2=80=99s inevitable: Tony and the gang are destined for=
 Netflix.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0</p></div>
